â“Q5: A server suddenly rebooted. How will you investigate?
âœ… Interview-Ready Answer:
â€œFirst, I check system logs in /var/log/messages or journalctl.
I verify last reboot time using last reboot and uptime.
I check dmesg for kernel panic or hardware errors.
I look for OOM killer events.
If it is due to power or VM issue, I coordinate with infra team.
Then I prepare RCA and preventive actions.â€
â“Q6: Application is running, but users say it is slow. CPU is normal. What next?
âœ… Answer:
â€œIf CPU is normal, I check memory and disk I/O.
I use iostat and vmstat to analyze wait time.
I check network latency using ping and traceroute.
I review application logs and DB connections.
Many times slowness is due to I/O or DB bottleneck.â€
â“Q7: What is Zombie process? How do you handle it?
âœ… Answer:
â€œA zombie process is a completed process whose entry remains in process table.
It happens when parent doesnâ€™t collect exit status.
I identify it using ps aux | grep Z.
Usually, restarting parent process clears it.
If many zombies appear, I investigate application bug.â€
â“Q8: How do you analyze high disk I/O wait?
âœ… Answer:
â€œI check %wa in top.
Then I use iostat -x to see device latency.
I find processes using iotop.
I check for heavy log writes, DB dumps, backups.
Then I optimize or schedule jobs off-peak.â€
â“Q9: What is OOM Killer?
âœ… Answer:
â€œOOM Killer is triggered when system runs out of memory.
Kernel kills high-memory processes to protect system.
I check dmesg and logs to confirm.
Then I tune application memory or add RAM/swap.â€
